social_posts.post_text:
Whenever I get asked to tell my story, I hesitate. A life that is constantly in motion, changes, growth and resilience. 

My story is an accumulation of coincidences, fate, unpredictable changes and hard work. How can I put a start to it when my ends are no where close. 

One thing for sure, is that I could never pretend something I didn't feel. I could never love if I didn't love, and I could never be me if I didn’t feel a lot. 

My only message behind my stories, is that everything worth fighting for, unbalances your life, but it’s all worth it in the end. 

This is my happy place. In the Arctic, and most specially, during the polar nights, when everything finally moves slower. 

@travelwithtjd

This memory makes my heart full. 

I’ve been looking back at some of the most memorable moments in my life, when I thought the impossible was unattainable. It’s a good reminder on how far I can go when I keep my happiness a priority. 

It’s a memory of me in 2016, freezing in the Arctic Ocean, being so present while on an icebreaker, I remember clearly thinking... I F**** did this. Solo. Just me.

I was so proud. 

Nothing is unattainable anymore... I’ll forever be in love with the Arctic.

This is for those who give everything to make their lives as beautiful as their dreams. ♥️

Her laugh is everything to me. ♥️

My decision to go to Antarctica was never to claim that I’ve been there, nor was I curious of the 7th continent. 

My decision to sail 23 days was to challenge myself. Despite the fear I’ve had and almost cancelling last minute, I challenged myself.

As an Arctic guide, I wanted to learn from those who were qualified to lead an expedition team to Antarctica. I wanted to grow and learn. I wanted to see the capacity of my strength in my mind. 

I knew that I won’t grow, expand and learn by doing only what I’m comfortable doing.

I’ll forever be grateful for my experiences on the journey to Antarctica and for the knowledge I took back with me. ♥️

This reminder is to the people in my life I’ve crossed paths with, especially on @travelwithtjd , who silently have their own struggles and wins, and, always a smile on their faces.
Choose growth... choose wisely. Be a giver, but not one without boundaries. Choose yourself first, no matter the noise around you. Strength is in letting go. So let go of what does not set your soul on fire 💫

The Arctic has become my home, my comfort zone. A place where I can easily and happily go to re-align my thoughts. An unforced bond. Nothing can take that away from me. 

I’m a forever kind of person. I no longer have room for temporary. 

If the Arctic gives me that peace of mind, how can I ever leave?

Today I met someone who didn’t know her self worth and it left me with a heavy heart. 
She admitted she wished for a lot of things and dreamed of accomplishing all her goals, but says it’s too late for her.
It reminded me of a story I read how we tend to create a big gap between expectations and reality, and we cannot see it. How we daydream for a perfect life and compare ourselves with irrelevant things, rather than be known for our growth, our accomplishments, and our compassion. 
It made me realize how much we always have to remember to be kind to ourselves and practice self-love. 
I hope you stop counting your mistakes and stop hurting with regret. 
I hope you love so strong, where you will always find the courage to say the things you wanted to say. 
I hope you never ever have to compare yourself to anyone but keep growing into the strong, smart and beautiful woman you are. 💫

It’s almost been a year since I’ve been on an expedition to Antarctica. I’ve learned so much then… I often look back to remind myself of what the 23 days at sea taught me. Part of me miss the learnings, and other part of me wants to adapt everything I learned, into another expedition. It’s the life of an Arctic guide. Missing those moments a little extra today. ♥️
We all want to belong ♥️
